{
  "doc_id": "7259",
  "text": "We further found that the locomotor skills of both boys and girls increased with age. As for object control skills and overall development, however, those between the ages of eight and nine performed better than the younger participants, but there was no significant difference between those aged between six and seven and those aged between seven and eight. This may be the result of the emphasis on such activities as stretching exercises, running, and skipping rope in physical education classes for first and second graders at Taiwanese elementary schools. Indeed, Payne and Isaacs [CITATION_1] assert that the content of physical education classes and how it is taught has an influence on the development of physical skills by children.",
